occurrenceRemarks: This was once referred to as the Pale Milksnake (L.t. "multistrata" in ancient times), before the nefarious historical event known as the "GTO" (the Great Taxonomic Obliteration", not the CAR)! Observed while lifting a flat rock on a sparsley-vegetated slope between the towns of Biddle and Broadus, MT. A juvenile specimen was also found nearby, which regurgitated a small Northern Sagebrush Lizard.
name: Lampropeltis gentilis (Baird & Girard, 1853)

occurrenceRemarks: Juvenile female "Pale" Milksnake - the recently-invalidated subspecies L. t. "multistrata". Discovered beneath a flat rock on a sparsely wooded slope between the towns of Biddle and Broadus, MT. Regurgitated a small Northern Sagebrush Lizard (S. g. graciosus) shortly after capture. An adult male "Pale" Milksnake was also found, within 50 feet of the specimen pictured.
name: Lampropeltis gentilis (Baird & Girard, 1853)

occurrenceRemarks: this same snake was caught and released on 1 June 2006, by Brian Nielsen, @ 23:30 hrs, at WGS 84, 40.5104921 N, 112.5300297W, elevation 5,680 feet.[X] Snake was identifed as the same individual by dorsal banding pattern of black-white-black "triads" - the posterior black band of triad #4 extends across the red band and contacts the anterior band of triad 15 - this exact same pattern is repeated in triads 32-33; an unmistakable pattern.

occurrenceRemarks: Found on side of trail, on south-facing slope. Struck and bit grinding teeth sideways when handled, but bite was painless and gave up when no apparent effect. Did not musk or defecate. Did not calm readily in hand and presented with striking, and jerky, sudden body movements until released. As of 2014, the taxonomic classification of the Milk Snake has changed such that it has been suggested that the previous 24 subspecies of the Milk Snake be divided into 7 distinct species. All of the subspecies that occur in Colorado are now lumped under Central Plains Milk Snake (Lampropeltis gentilis). I'm pretty sure that "Western Milk Snake" is a misnomer or a vestige from previous classification.

name: Lampropeltis gentilis (Baird & Girard, 1853)
identificationRemarks: iNaturalist currently follows the taxonomic proposal of Ruane et al., 2013. According to this proposal, specimens north of the Rio Grande are *L. gentilis*, while those south of the Rio Grande are *L. annulata*. Chambers and Hillis (2020 and others) have demonstrated (at least to my satisfaction) that this separation between western "*gentilis*," eastern "*triangulum*," and southern "*annulata*" as separate species is not biological reality and is an artifact of sampling bias and flawed interpretation of statistical analyses in subsequent publications. However, until iNaturalist updates its taxonomy, we're stuck calling these *L. gentilis*.

occurrenceRemarks: Found oddly under grass near a rock, basking in the morning sun. Oddly white near the tail, looked much closer to a pale milk from Weld than a front range milk, which was cool! Very difficult individual to photograph, and eventually escaped the photo session. Close by two other known individuals. Full sun and warming up rapidly, probably in the high 60s when encountered. Beautiful snake Jeffco
